     <p><strong><p><strong>Galen Strawson, <em>Stuff, Quality, Structure: The Whole Go</em>, Oxford University Press, 2024, 192pp., $50.00 (hbk) ISBN 9780198903659. </strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by David Builes, Princeton University</strong></p>
     <p>Galen Strawson’s <em>Stuff, Quality, Structure: The Whole Go</em> is an ambitious and wide-ranging work in fundamental metaphysics. Its primary goal is to present and defend an “identity metaphysics”, according to which many allegedly fundamental metaphysical distinctions are merely different ways of conceptualizing the same phenomena. There are many different components to Strawson’s identity metaphysics. One important claim is “categorical monism”, which is the view that there is only one fundamental ontological category, e.g., there is no real distinction between an object and the properties that it has. Another important claim is the so-called “powerful qualities” view, according to which there is no real distinction between the categorical properties of a thing and the corresponding causal powers (or dispositions) of a thing.</p> <p>Relatedly, according to Strawson, it...
